Consider the following:-

ImmutableMap&lt;String, String> map = ImmutableMap.builder().put("foo", "bar").build();

This doesn't compile because the compiler is unable to infer the generic type of the map which is rather irritating as you end up having to write this noise

ImmutableMap&lt;String, String> map = ImmutableMap.&lt;String, String>builder().put("foo", "bar").build();

I believe this could be fixed by adding a method like

public static &lt;K, V> Builder&lt;K, V> builder(K key, V value) {
&nbsp;&nbsp;return ImmutableMap.&lt;K, V>builder().put(key, value);
}

so a client could then write things much more concisely:-

ImmutableMap&lt;String, String> map = ImmutableMap.builder("foo", "bar").build();

It would be nice to call this method 'put' but that would duplicate the other put method.

